Oil Options Volatility Drops on Economic Growth in China, Europe

-- B y   L e e l a   L a n d r e s s
-- 
2011-07-05T19:45:31Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-05/oil-options-volatility-drops-on-economic-growth-in-china-europe.html
Oil options volatility fell as crude
oil climbed to the highest price in three weeks on signs of
economic growth in the U.S. and  China .  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
August, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of option prices, was 27.8 percent as of 3 p.m. in  New
York , down from 27.9 percent at the end of the day July 1.  Crude for August delivery gained $1.95 to $96.89 a barrel
on the  New York Mercantile Exchange , the highest settlement
price since June 14. Futures have gained 34 percent in a year.
Floor trading was closed yesterday for the U.S.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
August $100 calls, with 2,194 lots changing hands as of 3:43
p.m. They rose 18 cents to 62 cents a barrel. August $90 puts,
the next-most active option, fell 33 cents to 26 cents a barrel
with 1,280 lots trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of
crude.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occurs, the next business day.  December 2012 $80 puts were the most active options traded
July 1, with 4,553 lots changing hands. They lost 8 cents to
$5.22 a barrel. The next-most active options, October $80 puts,
rose 3 cents to 93 cents a barrel on volume of 4,244 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $120 calls with
43,219 contracts. Next were December $100 calls with 39,384 and
December $80 puts with 38,307.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Leela Landress in Houston at 
 llandress@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 